$ Oracle SQL functions related to text (VARCHAR2, NVARCHAR2, CHAR, NCHAR, CLOB and NCLOB)

table { ll
  ~Function~ ☰ ~Returns~
  `ascii` ☰ the decimal representation in the database character set of the first character of `char`
  `asciistr` ☰  → development/Unicode/ASCII version of string
  `chartorowid`, → development/databases/Oracle/SQL/functions/conversion/rowidtochar[`rowidtochar`], `rowidtonchar` ☰ a → development/databases/Oracle/SQL/data-types/rowid (and vice versa)
  → development/databases/Oracle/SQL/functions/text/chr-nchr[`chr`, `nchr`] ☰ → development/databases/Oracle/SQL/data-types/char[`char`] or `nchar` that corresponds to → development/Unicode/ASCII passed as argument
  `collation`, `nls_collation_name` ☰ name of → development/Unicode/collation[collation]
  `compose` ☰
  `concat` ☰ concatenated string
  `→ development/databases/Oracle/SQL/functions/text/convert` ☰ Convert a string from one → development/Unicode/character-set to another.
  `empty_clob` ☰ an empty → development/databases/Oracle/SQL/data-types/lob[CLOB] locator
  `hextoraw`, `rawtohex`, `rawtonhex` ☰ a → development/databases/Oracle/SQL/data-types/raw[RAW] that corresponds to the hexadecimal representation that was given as argument to `hextoraw`; and vice versa
  `initcap`, `nlsinitcap` ☰
  `instr` ☰
  `length` ☰ length of a string
  `lpad`, `rpad` ☰
  → development/databases/Oracle/SQL/functions/text/ltrim-rtrim-trim[`ltrim`, `rtrim`, `trim`] ☰ Removes spaces on one or both ends of a string.
  `lower`, `upper`, `nlslower`, `nlsupper` ☰
  `nlssort` ☰
  `reftohex` ☰
  `replace` ☰
  `soundex` ☰
  → development/databases/Oracle/SQL/functions/text/substr[`substr`] ☰ part of (longer) string
  → development/databases/Oracle/SQL/functions/type-conversion/to/char[`to_char`], `to_nchar`, `to_clob`, `to_nclob` ☰
  `to_multi_byte` ☰
  `translate`, `translate using` ☰ string where given set of characters are replaced with another set of characters
  `unistr` ☰
  → development/databases/Oracle/SQL/functions/type-conversion/validate_conversion[`validate_conversion`] ☰ a number that corresponds to the possibility to convert one → development/databases/Oracle/SQL/data-types[data type] to another

table }

{ Function name suffix

  Some functions come with different behavior that is indicated as suffix to the function name:
  table { ll
    `xxxB` ☰ Use bytes instead of characters
    `xxxC` ☰ Use → development/Unicode complete characters
    `xxx2` ☰ Use UCS2 code points
    `xxx4` ☰ Use UCS4 code points
  table }

  These functions are:
    • `instr`
    • `length`
    • `substr`
    • ???

